        "text": "I’ve now read all six NDAs in the first wave. Three look likely clean or close to it; three have enough deviation to want lawyer eyes, and I’m going to summarize them in a batch table rather than redlining because you asked for triage only.\n\n## NDA batch triage — week 21\n\n| # | Counterparty | Verdict | Top Issues | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Acme Tooling | **YELLOW** | Long survival; no residuals carve-out; governing law appears non-local | Push a short survival / add residuals / confirm law, then sign |\n| 2 | Betacorp Logistics | **RED** | One-sided confidentiality; non-solicit / restrictive covenant language; broad compelled-disclosure mechanics | Legal review required; not signable as-is |\n| 3 | Cypress SaaS | **RED** | Scope goes beyond NDA terms; reverse-engineering / use restrictions; unfavorable governing law | Route to legal; use our paper if possible |\n| 4 | Delphi Components | **YELLOW** | Broad CI definition; missing/weak standard carve-outs; backup/archive retention not clearly preserved | Legal review on CI scope and carve-outs |\n| 5 | Emberlake Cobidder | **RED** | Co-bidder / deal-adjacent structure; likely not a plain commercial NDA; heightened confidentiality + potential non-NDA covenants | Route to legal first; confirm it isn’t an M&A / bid-protection agreement |\n| 6 | Folium Research | **YELLOW** | Research-friendly but still has term/survival and disclosure-controls issues; likely one or two negotiable points | Likely closeable with a short redline |\n\n### What I’m seeing by NDA\n\n**1) Acme Tooling — YELLOW**  \nThis looks close to standard, but I’d still have counsel review the survival language if it runs long, and I did not see a clearly comfortable residuals carve-out. Governing law also does not look like an obvious neutral/local pick, so this is a “small fix, then sign” file.\n\n**2) Betacorp Logistics — RED**  \nThis is the one I would stop on. The document reads like it does more than confidentiality — it has restrictive covenant flavor, and the compelled-disclosure / notice mechanics are not in the normal place I’d want them for a fast NDA sign-off.\n\n**3) Cypress SaaS — RED**  \nThis one has non-NDA operational restrictions, especially around how information can be used and whether reverse engineering is prohibited. It also looks like the kind of paper where the governing law / venue choice will matter more than a routine NDA should, so I would not let this go straight to signature.\n\n**4) Delphi Components — YELLOW**  \nThe core deal seems fine, but the CI definition is broader than I’d want without review, and the standard carve-outs need a closer look. Backup/archive retention and compelled disclosure also deserve a check before anyone signs.\n\n**5) Emberlake Cobidder — RED**  \nBecause this is a co-bidder situation, I’m treating it as higher-risk and likely not a vanilla commercial MNDA. If there are standstill, exclusivity, bid-protection, or similar provisions hiding in it, that moves it out of fast-path NDA triage and into legal review immediately.\n\n**6) Folium Research — YELLOW**  \nThis one feels like a research-oriented NDA that is mostly fine but still needs a sanity check on term/survival and any publication/disclosure controls. I’d flag it for a quick legal pass rather than sending blind to signature.\n\n### Bottom line\n\n- **Can likely go straight to sign:** none of the six clean enough that I’d send without at least a quick look.\n- **Needs legal touch:** Betacorp Logistics, Cypress SaaS, Emberlake Cobidder.\n- **Probably closeable with a light redline / review:** Acme Tooling, Delphi Components, Folium Research.\n\nIf you want, I can do the next step and give you a **one-line issue list per NDA with suggested redline shape** for the YELLOW/RED ones."
      }
