n confidentiality undertaking; it surfaces 20 years later when no one remembers why and creates discovery exposure.\n- **Survival of more than 7 years** → YELLOW. Push to 3 years from disclosure unless there's a good reason (e.g., long-running regulatory matter, trade-secret content).\n- **Operative term of more than 5 years** → YELLOW. Most discussions are over within 12-18 months.\n\n## 2.2 Definition of Confidential Information\n\n- **Captures publicly available information** → YELLOW or RED depending on phrasing. \"Information that is publicly available but compiled or contextualised by the disclosing party\" is YELLOW; \"any information disclosed in any context\" is RED.\n- **Excludes residuals carve-out** → YELLOW. Sophisticated NDAs allow residuals retained in unaided memory of personnel; absence is a flag.\n- **Captures derivative works** → YELLOW. Standard wording covers the information itself, not derivative analysis the receiving party generates from public sources informed by the discussions.\n\n## 2.3 Carve-outs\n\n- **Missing standard carve-outs** (publicly known, prior knowledge, third-party receipt, independent development, compelled disclosure) → YELLOW or RED.\n- **Single-carve-out clauses** (\"only information already in our written records prior to disclosure\") → RED.\n- **Compelled-disclosure carve-out without prompt-notice obligation** → YELLOW. Buyer wants notice so they can seek a protective order; absence is a flag.\n\n## 2.4 Governing law and jurisdiction\n\n- **Governing law from a jurisdiction the receiving party doesn't operate in** → YELLOW. Push for our local law or a neutral choice (English law is widely acceptable).\n- **Exclusive jurisdiction in counterparty's home court** → YELLOW. Cost-of-litigation flag.\n- **Extraterritorial reach** (\"subject to the laws of [Texas / California / Singapore] without regard to conflict-of-laws principles\") → YELLOW or RED. Conflict-of-laws principles waiver is sometimes a smuggled forum-shopping play.\n\n## 2.5 Beyond-confidentiality clauses\n\nThese are often the real risk — clauses that aren't about confidentiality at all but get smuggled in under an NDA cover.\n\n- **Non-compete** → RED. Confidentiality and non-compete are different agreements; combining them is usually a sign of buyer trying to lock the seller out of a market via an NDA negotiating window.\n- **Non-solicitation** → YELLOW if narrow (employees actually in contact, 12 months); RED if broad (any employee, any indirect approach, 24+ months).\n- **IP assignment** → RED. NDAs are not the place for IP transfer. If the counterparty wants assignment, that's a separate paid licence or development agreement.\n- **Liquidated damages** → RED. The party drafting an NDA with a $500k-per-incident clause has thought hard about how to extract value from an alleged breach; we shouldn't sign without serious legal involvement.\n- **No-publicity clauses extending beyond announcing the deal** → YELLOW. Standard \"no public statements about the discussions\" is fine; \"no statements about the counterparty for 2 years post-termination\" is YELLOW.\n- **Reverse-engineering restrictions** in a confidentiality clause → YELLOW or RED depending on context. Make sense for software; not for general commercial NDAs.\n\n## 2.6 Mutual vs bilateral\n\n- **Mutual** NDAs apply confidentiality obligations to both parties. Preferred default for any two-way commercial discussion.\n- **Bilateral / one-way** NDAs apply obligations only to the receiving party. Acceptable when we are clearly receiving Confidential Information for a defined evaluation purpose (e.g., evaluating a vendor's pricing methodology). Not acceptable when there is genuine two-way disclosure.\n- **One-way running TO us as discloser** → GREEN typically.\n- **One-way running FROM us as receiver** without a clear scope → YELLOW.\n\n# 3. Output format\n\nFor batch review (multiple NDAs), produce a single table:\n\n| # | Counterparty | Verdict | Top Issues | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | [Counterparty A] | GREEN | none | Sign |\n| 2 | [Counterparty B] | YELLOW | Long survival, no residuals | Push to 3+3, add residuals, then sign |\n| 3 | [Counterparty C] | RED | Perpetual, no carve-outs, $500k LDs | Escalate to GC; not signable as drafted |\n\nFor per-NDA detail, follow with one paragraph each on the RED and YELLOW items, naming the clause and the proposed redline shape.\n\n# 4. Sign-off rules\n\n- **GREEN** — counsel sign or commercial sponsor sign with no legal involvement required.\n- **YELLOW** — counsel reviews and signs after redline; flag survival/CI-definition changes to the relationship lead.\n- **RED** — General Counsel must approve. Senior commercial sponsor must sign.\n\n# 5. Counterparty correspondence\n\nWhen responding to a RED NDA with substantive issues, write to the counterparty's legal team (not their commercial team — they will not have authority to amend their standard NDA). Use this shape:\n\n1. Thanks for the NDA.\n2. Identify the 2-3 issues we cannot accept (do not enumerate every YELLOW item — pick the ones that genuinely block).\n3. For each, name the clause and propose specific alternative wording.\n4. Offer to discuss; do not propose multiple alternatives in the first message (creates the impression of unlimited negotiating room).\n\n# 6. When this playbook does not apply\n\n- Settlement NDAs (different shape; usually negotiated with disputes counsel).\n- M&A confidentiality agreements (typically NDA + standstill + exclusivity; specialist M&A counsel).\n- Government / classified-information NDAs (specialist regulatory counsel).\n- Employment-related confidentiality undertakings (HR counsel).\n\nThis playbook covers commercial-counterparty NDAs. Anything else, escalate."
              }
